{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01KYfnBt1ettY2LWzr3QnHkE","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"There's a deployment error:\n```\njava.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: Failed to link org/webjars/servlet/WebjarsServlet: javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet\nCaused by: java.lang.ClassNotFoundException: javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet\n```\n\nThe `webjars-servlet-2.x` library version 1.6 still depends on the old `javax.servlet` API, not `jakarta.servlet`. I need to either:\n1. Remove the webjars-servlet dependency and serve webjars differently\n2. Or use a Jakarta EE-compatible webjars solution\n\nLet me check for a Jakarta EE-compatible version of the webjars servlet, or I can serve webjars directly from the WAR by extracting them or using a different approach.\n\nThe simplest approach is to remove the webjars-servlet dependency and instead configure the static resource serving differently. Since WildFly's Undertow already serves static resources from the WAR's web root, I can extract the webjar resources into the webapp directory during build, or I can use a Servlet Filter to serve them.\n\nActually, a better approach: let me check if there's a version of webjars-locator or webjars-servlet that supports Jakarta EE:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1755,"cache_read_input_tokens":87584,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1755,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":358},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"18927158-45c8-4480-8025-21200db12286","uuid":"371bca64-5621-490e-83c7-d7d681b39218"}
