{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_014XypPJozvsP5zP6r44P36n","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Let me think about this differently. The simplest solution for serving webjars in WildFly/Jakarta EE is to use `maven-dependency-plugin` to unpack the webjar resources into `webapp/webjars/` during build, OR to write a simple servlet that reads from classpath. But the quickest fix is to remove the WebjarsServlet and configure a simple servlet or use a different approach entirely.\n\nLet me just copy the webjar resources into the WAR's webapp directory during the Maven build:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":460,"cache_read_input_tokens":89339,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":460,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":230},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"18927158-45c8-4480-8025-21200db12286","uuid":"d535b83b-b78a-4655-bfaa-77407a11d2fc"}
